'''Hal Lebovitz''' (September 11, 1916 - October 18, 2005) was a longtime [[sportswriter]] and award-winning [[columnist]].<ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2005/10/19/hal_lebovitz_89_sports_columnist Hal Lebovitz, 89, sports columnist], ''[[The Boston Globe]]''. 2005-10-19.</ref> He was a fixture on [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]]'s sports scene for more than six decades. In 2000, he was inducted into the writer's wing of the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]].<ref>[http://web.baseballhalloffame.org/hofers/spink/lebovitz_hal.jsp Hal Lebovitz], National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum. Accessed 2007-07-07.</ref>

Born in Cleveland, he graduated from [[Glenville High School]] in 1934 and went on to [[Case Western Reserve University|Western Reserve University]] where he received a degree in [[chemistry]]. He had always wanted to be a [[journalist]], and he became the sports [[editing|editor]] of the [[student newspaper|school newspaper]].<ref>[http://www.clevelandseniors.com/people/lebovitz.htm Ask Hal - the Hall of Famer], Cleveland Seniors. Accessed 2007-07-07.</ref>

He got his first job covering high school sports for the ''[[Cleveland News]]'' in 1942 and soon became a [[beat writer]] covering the [[Cleveland Browns]] and the [[Cleveland Indians]]. He was hired by ''[[The Plain Dealer]]'' in 1960 and was the paper's sports editor from 1964 to 1982. His writing continued to appear regularly in ''[[The News-Herald (Ohio)|The News-Herald]]'' and ''[[The Morning Journal]]'' ([[Lorain, Ohio]]) until his death in 2005 at the age of 89.

He also coached baseball, basketball, and football and officiated all three sports, including a stint as a referee traveling with the [[Harlem Globetrotters]]. He was famous for his great knowledge of sports rules and wrote a popular newspaper column, "Ask Hal the Referee" which ran in both ''The Plain Dealer'' and ''[[The Sporting News]]'', in which he answered intricate questions about sports rules.<ref>"Ask Hal: Answers to Fans' Most Interesting Questions About Baseball Rules from a Hall-of-Fame Sportswriter", Gray & Company Publishers, Cleveland, 2004: ISBN 978-1-59851-034-8</ref>  

His writing was featured 17 times in the annual ''Best Sports Stories'' and selected for numerous other [[anthology|anthologies]]. He won countless writing awards and was inducted into 12 halls of fame.<ref>''The Best of Hal Lebovitz: Great Sportswriting from Six Decades in Cleveland''. Gray & Company Publishers: Cleveland, 2004. ISBN 978-1-59851-023-2</ref>

